context: The Order of Preachers (Latin: <a0_0><b6_0>Ordo Praedicatorum<b6_0/><a0_0/>, hence the abbreviation OP used by members), more commonly known after the 15th century as <a2_0>the <b5_0><b7_0>Dominican Order<a2_0/> or Dominicans<b7_0/><b5_0/>, is a <a3_0>Roman Catholic<a3_0/> religious order founded by the Spanish priest <a4_0>Saint Dominic de Guzman<a4_0/> in France and approved by <a1_0>Pope <b8_0>Honorius III<b8_0/><a1_0/> (1216–27) on 22 December 1216. Membership in this "mendicant" order includes <b9_0>friars, nuns, active sisters, and lay or secular Dominicans (formerly known as tertiaries<b9_0/>, though recently there has been a growing number of Associates, who are unrelated to the tertiaries) affiliated with the order.
